        "item": "Agitation and aggression",
        "notes_updates": "SAFETY IS THE FIRST PRIORITY! | Contain the patient to protect staff and self | VERBAL DE-ESCALATION - SAVE THE PATIENT: Support - Let's work together | Acknowledge - I see this is hard for you | Validate - I'd probably feel the same if I were you | Emotion Naming - You seem upset/angry/sad | Verbal de-escalation is most effective for mild/moderate agitation | Do not attempt to negotiate with a completely incoherent patient | AGITATION SEVERITY: MILD: Agitated but cooperative | MODERATE: Disruptive without danger | SEVERE: Threat to staff or self | EXTREME: High degree of agitation, Diaphoretic, tachypnoeic, hyperthermic, Unusual strength, Impervious to pain and fatigue, Unable to maintain attention, Incoherent, Severe metabolic acidosis | EXTREME AGITATION IS A LIFE-THREATENING EMERGENCY | PHYSICAL RESTRAINTS: Restraints must be prescribed by a doctor on Form 48 | Appropriate PPE for all staff involved | Never turn your back on the patient or become trapped in an enclosed space | At least 6 staff: 1 per limb, 1 to control the head, 1 to administer medication | NEVER restrain pts by placing pressure on the neck or covering the mouth and nose | Use 4 or 5 point medical grade restraints | Restrain in supine position with HOB 30 degrees up | Female pt: at least 1 female team member | Restraint time: 4 hours adults, 2 hours adolescents (9-17 years) | Tie restraints to bedframe, not rails | Ensure the airway is patent and maintained | Regular limb and pulse checks (30 mins) | Minimal time restrained, review regularly | Use in conjunction with chemical restraint, to avoid physical injury/rhabdomyolysis | Place an oxygen mask on the face to avoid biting/spitting | SEDATED PATIENTS MUST BE PLACED IN RECOVERY POSITION IN A MONITORED BED UNTIL THEY ARE FULLY AWAKE AND ALERT | ANY SEDATION CAN CAUSE RESPIRATORY DEPRESSION AND HYPOTENSION | RESUSCITATION FACILITIES MUST BE AVAILABLE | SPECIAL POPULATIONS: ELDERLY: avoid benzodiazepines. Consider 0.5 mg